ntinue to fail to address the interlinked challenges of systemic racism, inequalities faced by women, the Covid-19 pandemic and the nature and climate emergency.Across the world, economics students are coming together under the banner of the student movement, Rethinking Economics, to create a better economics – one which can help to create a world where all our children can flourish regardless of their gender, background or birthplace.Drawing on over sixty interviews with students and professionals from identities and backgrounds marginalised in economics and a wide range of global and historical research, this book illustrates the ways in which the discipline is currently not fit for purpose and sets out a vision for how it can be diversified, decolonised and democratised.The struggle to reclaim economics could not be more crucial - our futures depend on it. This book explains how it can be done.This book is relevant to United Nations Sustainable Development Goal 8, Decent work and economic growth  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aEconomic forecasting. 0aEconomicsxSociological aspects. 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / Education.2bisacsh  aDecent work and economic growth.  aEurocentricism.  aclimate crisis.  adecolonisation.  aeconomics education.  aeconomics profession.  aintersectionality.  anew economy movement.  asocial justice.  asystemic inequality.  asystems change.1 aAgunsoye, Ariane, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEarle, Joe, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aGhosh, Jayati, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGroenewald, Michelle, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGuizzo, Danielle, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRamburuth-Hurt